<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF107-983-112  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 983 112.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Reseller News  Dec 18 1989 n346 p37(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Bush pressed to ease export controls. (technology exports toEastern Bloc)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Hubbard, Holly.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The Bush administration is taking steps to lift US restrictions ontechnology exports to Eastern Europe in response to rapid changesin the region.andP;  It has formally agreed to re-examine the controls,with the stipulation that the countries involved agree to workwith the US government to prevent military technology from beingdiverted to neighboring Communist nations.andP;  The restrictions havebeen administered by the 17-nation Coordinating Committee onMultilateral Exports (COLCOM) for 40 years.andP;  Many COLCOM membersare also US allies and have been pressuring the US to ease traderestrictions.andP;  US officials are currently negotiating with Hungaryand Poland and expect to close a decision by mid-1990.andP;  CommerceSecretary Robert Mosbacher is an advocate of loosertechnology-export controls; Defense Secretary Dick Cheney opposesany change, saying that it would jeopardize national defense.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     International TradeMicrocomputersEastern EuropeExportPolitical IssuesComputer IndustryCoordinating Committee for Multilateral Export ControlsUnited States. Department of DefenseUnited States. Department of Commerce.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>